65 ) last Friday:

It=E2=80=99s been a few days since pretty much every major third-party Twit=
ter client broke, and developers say they still haven=E2=80=99t heard anyth=
ing from the company about what=E2=80=99s going on. The issues seemed to be=
gin on Thursday evening, with some users reporting that they were getting e=
rrors related to authentication ( https://mastodon.world/@caseynewton@masto=
don.social/109679932869920307 ). The silence from the company has been pret=
ty much complete. =E2=80=9CStill no official/unofficial info from inside Tw=
itter,=E2=80=9D said Tweetbot co-creator Paul Haddad in a Mastodon post ( h=
ttps://tapbots.social/@paul/109684886363418765 ). =E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99re in=
 the dark just as much as you are,=E2=80=9D read a Friday blog post ( https=
://blog.iconfactory.com/2023/01/state-of-the-twitterverse/ ) from Iconfacto=
ry, the company behind Twitterific.

The Information reported on Saturday ( https://www.theinformation.com/artic=
les/musks-twitter-intentionally-suspended-tweet-bot-third-party-apps-messag=
es-show ) that the outage wasn=E2=80=99t an accident:

The mysterious outage of Tweetbot and other third-party Twitter clients tha=
t began Thursday night was an intentional suspension, according to internal=
 messages viewed by The Information. The suspension cut off the ability of =
people to use Twitter on outside apps, forcing them to go to Twitter=E2=80=
=99s own app. The reason for the suspension couldn=E2=80=99t be learned. Sp=
eculation on one blog ( https://9to5google.com/2023/01/12/twitter-api-appea=
rs-to-be-down-breaking-tweetbot-and-third-party-clients/ ) this week raised=
 the possibility that Twitter might have turned off access to the apps deli=
berately because they don=E2=80=99t help drive ad revenue. At least some do=
n=E2=80=99t show ads that appear on Twitter. That means the apps may be hur=
ting Elon Musk=E2=80=99s ability to stop a major decline in ad revenue ( ht=
tps://www.theinformation.com/articles/twitters-efforts-to-court-advertisers=
-turns-them-off ) in the past two months=E2=80=A6

The internal messages seen by The Information also show that Twitter employ=
ees have been discussing when the decision would be announced publicly. A T=
witter employee working on product partnerships asked on Friday morning whe=
n employees could expect a list of =E2=80=9Capproved talking points=E2=80=
=9D for questions from partners related to =E2=80=9C3party clients revoked =
access.=E2=80=9D A product marketing manager responded on Slack that mornin=
g that the company had =E2=80=9Cstarted to work on comms=E2=80=9D but that =
there was no estimate as to when it would be ready, the messages show.

This decision is classic Musk, but to fully understand why it=E2=80=99s imp=
ortant to understand some context behind this move.

Twitter=E2=80=99s Tortured History With 3rd-Party Apps
----------------------------------------------

I=E2=80=99ve written about Twitter=E2=80=99s history with 3rd-party apps on=
 several occasions, including in 2022=E2=80=99s Back to the Future of Twitt=
er ( https://stratechery.com/2022/back-to-the-future-of-twitter/?access_tok=
en=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsIn=
R5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUiLCJlbnQiOnsi=
dXJpIjpbImh0dHBzOi8vc3RyYXRlY2hlcnkuY29tLzIwMjIvYmFjay10by10aGUtZnV0dXJlLW9=
mLXR3aXR0ZXIvIl19LCJleHAiOjE2NzY0NjE3MjMsImlhdCI6MTY3Mzg2OTcyMywiaXNzIjoiaH=
R0cHM6Ly9zdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUvb2F1dGgiLCJzY29wZSI6ImZlZWQ6c=
mVhZCBhcnRpY2xlOnJlYWQgYXNzZXQ6cmVhZCBjYXRlZ29yeTpyZWFkIiwic3ViIjoiUnNldVlF=
OGpnSGVQcFdKZjFmQWI0QyIsInVzZSI6ImFjY2VzcyJ9.Er3DumTN_6baOMTKjSVYIt5PxXz3OG=
BAA8yPR66MrnB2IGkH5v8A4ywQfaGcsCHCGk2-Tmi9qTFVTOl3mrC7dfBYVvp7LCsPpkwlamcu6=
vrFHQ3b8JR9edIdQccGxG_Wg25Z2WPQ3Z_pc47KGmdJ7yy52R32orCeSJ7oOfuHzwLl4L7S4m0U=
EorVAIXiXMz0jJ7-yt1_2rFe6eCyYaduwFzTVm186dyDGE5HHsLJW-Rhezew7uHunv_Ln4lnUCS=
O5PRojtHhxjJjvoFouGWctqnMUxBZ4fI9_rHsva1eHDO2CKO6_COG3MEvAIGPixbJ8yJBcouHlG=
LCFU6M4lYhUQ ) :

The general idea behind a services architecture is that various functionali=
ties are exposed via application programming interfaces, more commonly know=
n as APIs; a =E2=80=9Cclient=E2=80=9D will leverage these APIs to build an =
end user experience. There is no requirement that these clients be owned or=
 managed by the centralized service, and for the first several years of Twi=
tter=E2=80=99s existence, that is exactly how the service operated: Twitter=
 the company ran the service and the Twitter.com website, while third-parti=
es built clients that let you access Twitter first on the desktop and then =
on smartphones.

Mobile was an absolute boon for Twitter: the public messaging service, mode=
led on SMS, was a natural fit for a smartphone screen, and the immediacy of=
 Twitter updates was perfectly suited to a device that was always connected=
 to the Internet. The explosion in mobile usage, though, led to a situation=
 where Twitter didn=E2=80=99t actually control the user experience for a hu=
ge portion of its users. This actually led to a ton of innovation: Twitterr=
ific, for example, the earliest third party client, came up with the Twitte=
r bird, the term =E2=80=9Ctweet=E2=80=9D for a Twitter message, and early p=
aradigms around replies and conversations. It also led to problems, the sol=
utions to which fundamentally changed Twitter=E2=80=99s potential as a busi=
ness.

The first problem that came from Twitter the service relying on third party=
 clients is that the company, which descended into politics and backstabbin=
g from the board level on down almost immediately, was drifting along witho=
ut a business model; the obvious candidate was advertising, but the easiest=
 way to implement advertising was to control the user interface (and thus i=
nsert ads =E2=80=94 ads, including promoted tweets, are another distinct se=
rvice from Twitter itself). Thus Twitter bought Tweetie, widely regarded as=
 the best Twitter mobile client (I was a user), in April 2010, and rebrande=
d and relaunched it as the official Twitter for iPhone app a month later.

The second problem is that starting in 2010, a Silicon Valley entrepreneur =
named Bill Gross (who invented search advertising) started trying to build =
his own Twitter monetization product called TweetUp; when Twitter acquired =
Tweetie and made clear they were going to monetize it via advertising, Gros=
s started buying up multiple other third party Twitter clients with the ide=
a of creating a competing network of clients that would monetize independen=
tly. Twitter responded in the short term by kicking several of Gross=E2=80=
=99s clients off of the platform for dubious terms-of-service violations, a=
nd in the long term by killing the 3rd party API for everyone. Clients coul=
d keep the users they had but could only add 100,000 more users =E2=80=94 e=
ver.

The net result of these two decisions was that Twitter, its architecture no=
twithstanding, would be a unified entity where Twitter the company controll=
ed every aspect of the experience, and that that experience would be moneti=
zed via advertising.

The context of that Article was my proposal that Musk leverage the freedom =
of being a private company to split Twitter into a service and an app; the =
app might continue to be supported by advertising, but other apps could bui=
ld on the Twitter service in exchange for paying some sort of fee (that the=
y could recoup with their own advertising or, more likely, subscriptions).

It=E2=80=99s important to note, though, that the continued existence of thi=
rd-party apps post that 2012 decision made zero business sense. Think again=
 about the rationale for what was an exceptionally controversial decision: =
Twitter needed to IPO, and it felt that advertising was the best business m=
odel to pursue; whether or not you agree with that decision, once that deci=
sion was made it made perfect sense to force everyone to use the Twitter ap=
p. Remember, effective digital advertising isn=E2=80=99t simply about servi=
ng ads: it=E2=80=99s also about understanding the interests of the user, an=
d even if Twitter put ads into its API (which it never did), it would have =
been a difficult undertaking to build the ability to capture those interest=
s into an API to the same extent it could with its own client.

The hallmark of Twitter leadership for its entire pre-Musk existence, thoug=
h, has been weakness and an aversion to conflict (which, paradoxically, led=
 to more conflict, particularly internally). That=E2=80=99s how we ended up=
 with a ridiculous situation where 3rd-party Twitter clients were allowed t=
o continue to exist, and add up to 100,000 new users; the fact of the matte=
r is that if Twitter were committed to an advertising business model it sho=
uld have just pulled the plug completely.

Now, let me be very clear: I love and use 3rd-party Twitter clients. I actu=
ally used three Twitter clients: the official Twitter app, Tweetbot, and Tw=
eetlogix (which had an amazing ability to search =E2=80=98Stratechery=E2=80=
=99 and capture every tweet that mentioned it without losing its place in t=
ime). Most of my Twitter usage was in the main Twitter app, both because I =
preferred the algorithmic timeline and because its direct message support w=
as better =E2=80=94 messages were both faster, and it was the only way to p=
artake in group DMs. That latter point, though, only points to how ridiculo=
us the situation became over the years: new Twitter features like polls and=
 group DMs only ever came to the official Twitter app; 3rd-party apps were =
being dragged along like some sort of vestigial limb that wasn=E2=80=99t pa=
rticularly pleasant for either Twitter or 3rd-party app developers.

So here=E2=80=99s the thing: from a pure business sense killing 3rd-party c=
lients made perfect sense, and it is an indictment of Twitter=E2=80=99s pre=
vious management that they didn=E2=80=99t do it in 2012, or at any other po=
int afterwards. It is a credit to Musk that, given he seems insistent on ma=
king the advertising model work, he did what needed to be done. And yet =E2=
=80=94 and this is what makes this move classic Musk =E2=80=94=C2=A0he exec=
uted this decision in the worst way possible. Craig Hockenberry, who create=
d Twitterrific for Iconfactory, and who bears more responsibility for Twitt=
er=E2=80=99s development than anyone never employed by Twitter, wrote on hi=
s blog ( https://furbo.org/2023/01/15/the-shit-show/ ) :

My mom passed away just before Christmas. Her decline was something everyon=
e in the family saw coming and we prepared for her demise. It still hurts l=
ike hell, but she left with love and dignity. That makes all the difference=
 when it comes to coping with loss.

Twitterrific is something that we=E2=80=99ve all ( https://iconfactory.com/=
#aboutus ) poured our love into for the past 16 years ( https://blog.iconfa=
ctory.com/2007/01/introducing-twitterrific/ ). I=E2=80=99m not usually one =
to toot my own horn, but we literally crafted the early experience ( https:=
//furbo.org/2011/03/11/twitterrific-firsts/ ) on the service. We often hear=
 that folks joined up because of our app. Our work was definitive and groun=
dbreaking ( https://iconfactory.com/twitterrific_touch/ ). We loved this ap=
p like I loved my mom=E2=80=A6

Like my mom, the API has been declining for awhile. Endpoints were removed,=
 new features were unavailable to third parties, and rate limiting restrict=
ed what we could do. And like my mom, we struggled on and did the best we c=
ould, trying to stay upbeat about it all.

What bothers me about Twitterrific=E2=80=99s final day is that it was not d=
ignified. There was no advance notice for its creators, customers just got =
a weird error, and no one is explaining what=E2=80=99s going on. We had no =
chance to thank customers who have been with us for over a decade. Instead,=
 it=E2=80=99s just another scene in their ongoing shit show.

Again, I absolutely believe there is a business case for killing 3rd-party =
apps (although again, I would have gone in the opposite direction), and tha=
t business case suggests it should have happened a decade ago. That doesn=
=E2=80=99t change the fact that this arbitrary cut-off, with zero announcem=
ent or warning, was an exceptionally crappy way to go about it.

The Twitter Files Business Model
--------------------------------

I haven=E2=80=99t written about Twitter in a while, and not just because th=
e topic has become incredibly polarized and thus, in my experience, immune =
from any sort of arms-length analysis. I think, though, this cut-off was an=
 important tell about Twitter=E2=80=99s business model going forward.

First, I think this move is potentially a signal that Twitter Blue has alre=
ady been deemed a failure. After all, an obvious Twitter Blue feature would=
 be the ability to use third-party apps. Perhaps this is still on the table=
, and maybe developers like Iconfactory with pre-existing apps and userbase=
s would come back to the table. To say that Twitter=E2=80=99s relationship =
with 3rd-party developers was already rocky, though, is a massive understat=
ement, and after this weekend it seems insane to ever trust Twitter again.

Second, I think the Twitter Files are instructive. There is a lot of conste=
rnation as to why the revelation that Twitter was very much enmeshed with t=
he federal government in terms of controlling speech on Twitter is not a bi=
g story; for the record, I think it is scandalous, and fundamentally agains=
t the principle and ethos of free speech, even if illegality may be difficu=
lt to establish. The reason why the story hasn=E2=80=99t resonated, though,=
 has, I think, to do with the =E2=80=9Ccertain conditions=E2=80=9D Matt Tai=
bbi referenced on his Substack ( https://taibbi.substack.com/p/note-to-read=
ers-8d4 ). He explained ( https://taibbi.substack.com/p/note-to-readers-on-=
the-twitter-files ) after several threads had been posted:

In the rush to get all this done, I chose words poorly. A lot has been made=
 about the line about how I =E2=80=9Chad to agree to certain conditions=E2=
=80=9D to work on the story. I wrote that assuming the meaning of that line=
 would be obvious. It was obvious. Still, the language was just loose enoug=
h to give critics room to make mischief, and the stakes being what they are=
, they of course did. That=E2=80=99s on me, and a lesson going forward. For=
 the record, the deal was access to the Twitter documents, but I had to pub=
lish on Twitter. I also agreed to an attribution (=E2=80=9CSources at Twitt=
er=E2=80=9D). That=E2=80=99s it=E2=80=A6

One last quick note. I was very skeptical at first about using Twitter to b=
reak these stories. Not only am I not exactly a skilled Tweeter (as, sadly,=
 people have seen in the last weeks), but I worried about the logistical ch=
allenge of telling complex stories in 140-character chunks. It seemed impos=
sible. Two weeks later, I feel differently. In this particular instance, th=
e story has to come out on Twitter. There=E2=80=99s the obvious deep irony =
of using the familiar drip-drip-drip format and uncontrollable virality of =
Twitter to roast Twitter itself. We=E2=80=99re also using an inherently des=
tabilizing medium to expose efforts to turn Twitter into an authoritarian i=
nstrument of social control. There=E2=80=99s genius in this. Now I would fe=
el wrong even thinking of doing it any other way.

For the record, I disagree: I think dripping out the Twitter Files on Twitt=
er blunted their impact substantially; Twitter=E2=80=99s power is in its or=
chestration of consent, not in the ability of any one tweet to pierce conse=
nsus. Take, for example, one of the most impactful stories of the pandemic:=
 Nicholson Baker=E2=80=99s article in New York Magazine about The Lab-Leak =
Hypothesis ( https://nymag.com/intelligencer/article/coronavirus-lab-escape=
-theory.html ). There is currently this paragraph appended at the top:

When Nicholson Baker published =E2=80=9CThe Lab-Leak Hypothesis=E2=80=9D in=
 early January, the subject itself was still deeply taboo across the Americ=
an political and journalistic landscape. A year later, the hypothesis has b=
een revived and reconsidered not just by major investigations by the New Yo=
rk Times, The Wall Street Journal, the Washington Post, and The Atlantic, b=
ut also by the WHO and the U.S. Intelligence Community. Nearly everything t=
hat would later serve as the basis for this public reconsideration of pande=
mic origins was contained in Baker=E2=80=99s original story, the first of i=
ts kind to break the ice.

The lab leak hypothesis was not original to Baker=E2=80=99s story; it was w=
idespread on Twitter in particular. The fact of the matter is, though =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0and I say this as an independent blogger who is not part of the=
 mainstream media =E2=80=94 New York Magazine does have justification for b=
eing proud of having published the story; breaking the ice in the mainstrea=
m media is, for better a worse, a meaningful accomplishment. By extension, =
publishing the Twitter Files on Twitter all but assured they would receive =
no attention from the mainstream media; if they can=E2=80=99t have first di=
bs, then they are more than content to pretend the story doesn=E2=80=99t ex=
ist.

What does justify this approach, though, is thinking about the Twitter File=
s as engagement bait. It seems probable that Musk is skeptical of the value=
 of Twitter pushing people to content off of Twitter; if Twitter is so impo=
rtant as connective tissue, why not capture the value directly on Twitter i=
tself? After all, the more essential Twitter is not just in terms of links =
but in terms of content, the more advertisers will have no choice but to be=
 on Twitter instead of the sites that are linked to. That, at least, seems =
to be the theory; I=E2=80=99m not sure how well it will work, but it seems =
in-line with the decisions made over the past weekend.

